SIMPLE: imparlance
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Imparlance
<hw>Im*par"lance</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf.
<er>Emparlance</er>, <er>Parlance</er>.]</ety> <altsp>[Written also
<asp>inparliance</asp>.]</altsp> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Mutual discourse;
conference.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Law)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>Time given to a party
to talk or converse with his opponent, originally with the object of
effecting, if possible, an amicable adjustment of the suit. The actual
object, however, has long been merely to obtain further time to plead,
or answer to the allegations of the opposite party.</def> <sd>(b)</sd>
<def>Hence, the delay or continuance of a suit.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ <xex>Imparlance</xex> and <xex>continuance by
imparlance</xex> have been abolished in England.</note> <rj><au>Wharton
(Law Dict. ).</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Imparsonee</ent>⟦br⟧
